    "created_at": "2018-11-18T11:50:30Z",
    "updated_at": "2018-11-18T11:50:30Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "My advice to move the logic into `ITick` was a *very* bad idea, and will need to be reverted.  The bot logic runs locally in an unsynced context, while tick runs everywhere in a synced context.\r\n\r\nThis leads to two issues:\r\n* The AI code runs on all clients, causing a lot of unnecessary perf overhead, and generates spurious \"exploit order\" warnings on clients who aren't the host\r\n![screenshot 2018-11-18 at 11 00 34](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/167819/48671910-e64eab00-eb26-11e8-92a0-42f73e0f2269.png)\r\n* The ambiguity will, i'm quite sure, lead to confusion and future use of synced code that will cause desyncs.\r\n\r\nThe fix here is to reintroduce an interface like the following:\r\n```csharp\r\npublic interface IBotTick { void BotTick(BotOrderManager botOrderManager) }\r\n```\r\n\r\nInstances of the trait would be cached in the AI traits, and then called as:\r\n```csharp\r\nSync.CheckSyncUnchanged(world, () =>\r\n{\r\n\tforeach (var t in tickModules)\r\n\t\tif (t.IsTraitEnabled())\r\n\t\t\tt.Tick(botOrderManager);\r\n});\r\n\r\n```\r\n\r\nIMO it is more flexible to have multiple `IBotTick`, `IBotProduction`, `IBotRespondToAttack` etc than a monolithic `IBotModule` - this allows mods to introduce their own inter-module plumbing without having to modify the base definition."
